# Node.js Backend Conventions

## General
- Use TypeScript with strict mode for all backend code.
- Use `async/await` over raw promises or callbacks.
- All environment-dependent values come from env vars or config files — no hardcoded secrets.
- Use structured logging (e.g., `pino` or `winston`) at `info` level minimum; no `console.log` in production code.

## Project Structure
- Keep game logic (state, physics, combat) separate from transport (WebSocket/HTTP handlers).
- Use a service layer between routes/handlers and data access.
- Shared types between client and server go in a `shared/` directory.

## WebSocket / Multiplayer
- All real-time game communication uses WebSockets (e.g., Socket.IO or ws).
- Validate every incoming message — never trust client data.
- Server is authoritative for game state (position, HP, damage, loot).
- Use rooms/channels for multiplayer sessions (up to 4 players per room).

## Error Handling
- Wrap async route/handler functions to catch unhandled rejections.
- Return meaningful error codes and messages to clients.
- Never expose internal stack traces to clients.

## Testing
- Use Jest for unit and integration tests.
- Game logic (damage calc, stat formulas, leveling) must have unit tests.
- Mock external dependencies (DB, network) in tests.

## Dependencies
- Keep dependencies minimal and justified.
- Pin major versions in `package.json`.
- Prefer well-maintained packages with active communities.
